00:00:11.060 --> 00:00:14.240
PETER DIAMANDIS: Thank you,
Jack, a force of nature here.

00:00:14.240 --> 00:00:16.570
So, a pleasure to be here.

00:00:16.570 --> 00:00:20.150
I want to just actually tee up
a bunch of quick conversations

00:00:20.150 --> 00:00:23.690
that we can carry to our
fireside chat and conversation

00:00:23.690 --> 00:00:25.050
with you.

00:00:25.050 --> 00:00:27.380
So first of all,
I'm clear that we're

00:00:27.380 --> 00:00:29.300
alive during the most
extraordinary time

00:00:29.300 --> 00:00:30.980
ever in human history.

00:00:30.980 --> 00:00:34.250
There's never been a better time
to be alive, other than perhaps

00:00:34.250 --> 00:00:35.530
tomorrow.

00:00:35.530 --> 00:00:37.400
We're in a time
where each of us have

00:00:37.400 --> 00:00:42.500
more power than nation-states
had, heads of industries had,

00:00:42.500 --> 00:00:45.320
just decades or a century ago.

00:00:45.320 --> 00:00:48.290
We forget how
amazing the world is.

00:00:48.290 --> 00:00:53.660
We forget that 100 years ago,
in 1918, in that one year

00:00:53.660 --> 00:00:58.640
alone, 50 million people
died from the Spanish flu.

00:00:58.640 --> 00:01:02.146
20-odd million people died
from World War I. Scale that

00:01:02.146 --> 00:01:03.770
to today's population,
you'd be talking

00:01:03.770 --> 00:01:05.228
about a quarter of
a billion people

00:01:05.228 --> 00:01:06.980
that would have
passed away this year.

00:01:06.980 --> 00:01:11.030
So we forget, despite all
of the negative news--

00:01:11.030 --> 00:01:13.350
what I call the Crisis
News Network and so forth--

00:01:13.350 --> 00:01:16.310
we're still living
in an amazing time.

00:01:16.310 --> 00:01:18.140
It's also true that
I think none of us

00:01:18.140 --> 00:01:21.870
really understand how fast
the world is changing.

00:01:21.870 --> 00:01:26.210
We're living in a world where
technologies across the board

00:01:26.210 --> 00:01:27.890
are growing exponentially.

00:01:27.890 --> 00:01:30.830
Computation, sensors, networks,
AI, robotics, 3D printing,

00:01:30.830 --> 00:01:33.560
synthetic biology, AR, VR, block
chain-- all those technologies

00:01:33.560 --> 00:01:35.450
are themselves accelerating.

00:01:35.450 --> 00:01:37.700
But it's the combination
of two, three, or four

00:01:37.700 --> 00:01:41.450
of those together that
are accelerating things.

00:01:41.450 --> 00:01:43.820
Add to that the notion
that in the next six years,

00:01:43.820 --> 00:01:46.340
we're going from 3.8 billion
people connected on planet

00:01:46.340 --> 00:01:50.030
Earth last year at the end
of 2017 to 8 billion people

00:01:50.030 --> 00:01:50.660
connected.

00:01:50.660 --> 00:01:54.200
We're adding 4 billion new minds
into the global conversation

00:01:54.200 --> 00:01:56.910
that have never
been there before.

00:01:56.910 --> 00:01:59.912
And that's a massive
empowerment for acceleration.

00:01:59.912 --> 00:02:01.370
Add to that the
fact that we've got

00:02:01.370 --> 00:02:05.270
more capital available,
flowing, than ever before.

00:02:05.270 --> 00:02:09.009
We hit all-time highs in
venture fund, seed funding,

00:02:09.009 --> 00:02:13.580
crowdfunding, ICOs,
sovereign investments.

00:02:13.580 --> 00:02:15.980
So more capital flowing
at the same time

00:02:15.980 --> 00:02:18.560
that all the technology that
we're using to make stuff

00:02:18.560 --> 00:02:22.010
happen is demonetizing
faster than ever before.

00:02:22.010 --> 00:02:27.000
The human genome was sequenced
for $100 million in 2001.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:29.480
Today it's circa $500.

00:02:29.480 --> 00:02:32.240
Illumina is projecting
$100 in one hour,

00:02:32.240 --> 00:02:34.310
as is the Beijing
Genome Institute.

00:02:34.310 --> 00:02:36.230
So there's more money.

00:02:36.230 --> 00:02:38.000
Everything we need
to do is cheaper.

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:41.810
Look at Google Cloud and
computational capabilities.

00:02:41.810 --> 00:02:45.110
And so more people, more
money, cheaper stuff,

00:02:45.110 --> 00:02:46.890
more experimentation.

00:02:46.890 --> 00:02:48.800
And what it means
is we're entering

00:02:48.800 --> 00:02:52.130
a period of hyper-acceleration.

00:02:52.130 --> 00:02:55.160
As I think about how
fast the world is going,

00:02:55.160 --> 00:02:56.580
it's not slowing down.

00:02:56.580 --> 00:02:59.030
And in fact, it's
an acceleration

00:02:59.030 --> 00:03:01.160
of the acceleration
that we're hitting.

00:03:01.160 --> 00:03:04.170
So that makes for an
amazing, amazing future.

00:03:04.170 --> 00:03:07.400
And one of the things that I
focus on a lot is the notion

00:03:07.400 --> 00:03:10.490
that there is no
problem we cannot solve.

00:03:10.490 --> 00:03:14.570
And I'm clear that the right
combination of technology,

00:03:14.570 --> 00:03:18.490
talent, and treasure
can take on any problem.

00:03:18.490 --> 00:03:20.600
And my message to a lot
of people around the world

00:03:20.600 --> 00:03:22.880
is you're now empowered.

00:03:22.880 --> 00:03:24.830
If you are sick and
tired about a problem

00:03:24.830 --> 00:03:29.120
or you're inspired to
solve something, you can.

00:03:29.120 --> 00:03:31.190
It's a matter of do
you give yourself

00:03:31.190 --> 00:03:34.320
permission to be that
audacious and go do it?

00:03:34.320 --> 00:03:37.580
100 years ago, the only people
could actually solve a problem

00:03:37.580 --> 00:03:42.110
at any scale were
the nation-states

00:03:42.110 --> 00:03:45.050
or were the robber barons,
the industrialists.

00:03:45.050 --> 00:03:48.680
And even all they could do
was unleash monetary policies

00:03:48.680 --> 00:03:51.140
or troops or so forth.

00:03:51.140 --> 00:03:54.170
Today, I just want you
to feel and understand

00:03:54.170 --> 00:03:57.900
how empowered you are to find
a problem and solve a problem.

00:03:57.900 --> 00:04:01.490
That's what gives me hope, that
entrepreneurs by definition

00:04:01.490 --> 00:04:04.211
are individuals who find
problems and solve problems.

00:04:04.211 --> 00:04:05.960
And there are more and
more entrepreneurs,

00:04:05.960 --> 00:04:08.334
with more and more data, with
more and more computational

00:04:08.334 --> 00:04:10.790
power, with more and
more access to capital,

00:04:10.790 --> 00:04:12.910
solving more and more problems.

00:04:12.910 --> 00:04:16.800
So I want to give you that
perspective for a moment.

00:04:16.800 --> 00:04:19.876
Another area I'm
excited about, I

00:04:19.876 --> 00:04:21.500
serve as founder and
executive chairman

00:04:21.500 --> 00:04:23.510
of the XPRIZE Foundation.

00:04:23.510 --> 00:04:27.050
Jack is-- for a while now,
since the earliest days--

00:04:27.050 --> 00:04:29.620
one of my trustees.

00:04:29.620 --> 00:04:33.985
And so we focus on what are the
world's biggest problems that

00:04:33.985 --> 00:04:35.650
are not being solved?

00:04:35.650 --> 00:04:37.870
And how do we set a
very clear objective

00:04:37.870 --> 00:04:39.795
and say, I don't
care who you are

00:04:39.795 --> 00:04:41.920
or where you went to school,
what you've ever done,

00:04:41.920 --> 00:04:45.390
if you solve this problem and
hit these metrics, you win.

00:04:45.390 --> 00:04:50.410
And to the very first XPRIZE
was for my 9-year-old childhood

00:04:50.410 --> 00:04:51.370
passion of spaceflight.

00:04:51.370 --> 00:04:54.500
I gave up on NASA being the
way I was going to go to space.

00:04:54.500 --> 00:04:56.950
I did the math, and your
chance are-- right, Mark?--

00:04:56.950 --> 00:05:00.310
one in 1,000 of being
a NASA astronaut.

00:05:00.310 --> 00:05:02.680
I had a better chance of
becoming an NBA all-star at 5'

00:05:02.680 --> 00:05:05.200
5" than I did a NASA astronaut.

00:05:05.200 --> 00:05:08.410
And so when I read
that Lindbergh in 1927

00:05:08.410 --> 00:05:11.170
crossed the Atlantic
to win a $25,000 prize

00:05:11.170 --> 00:05:14.020
and looked at the
numbers, nine teams

00:05:14.020 --> 00:05:17.920
spent $400,000 trying to
win this $25,000 prize.

00:05:17.920 --> 00:05:21.880
And Raymond Orteig spent
nothing on the losers, only paid

00:05:21.880 --> 00:05:22.750
the winner.

00:05:22.750 --> 00:05:25.150
And Lindbergh was the most
unlikely guy to do it.

00:05:25.150 --> 00:05:27.740
So I said, OK, I'm going to
create a prize for spaceflight.

00:05:27.740 --> 00:05:29.440
It's going to be a
$10 million prize.

00:05:29.440 --> 00:05:32.740
$10 million was enough money
to inspire the entrepreneurs,

00:05:32.740 --> 00:05:34.810
but not the Airbus, the
Boeing, the Lockheed.

00:05:34.810 --> 00:05:37.600
I didn't want the large
players just buying the prize.

00:05:37.600 --> 00:05:40.030
I wanted true innovation.

00:05:40.030 --> 00:05:43.152
That $10 million prize
inspired 26 teams

00:05:43.152 --> 00:05:44.860
around the world, who
spent $100 million.

00:05:44.860 --> 00:05:46.840
They're all optimists.

00:05:46.840 --> 00:05:51.790
And Burt Rutan, backed by
Paul Allen, who we just lost,

00:05:51.790 --> 00:05:56.080
funded that prize development
and won it with SpaceShip One.

00:05:56.080 --> 00:05:58.510
Richard Branson came in
and bought the rights

00:05:58.510 --> 00:06:00.550
to create Virgin Galactic.

00:06:00.550 --> 00:06:04.330
Richard has publicly announced
he expects a flight to space

00:06:04.330 --> 00:06:06.100
approximately this month.

00:06:06.100 --> 00:06:07.980
So fingers crossed
we'll see something.

00:06:07.980 --> 00:06:09.980
There's-- what?-- three
weeks left in the month,

00:06:09.980 --> 00:06:12.320
or thereabouts.

00:06:12.320 --> 00:06:16.720
And then we, on the heels of
that, created an amazing board.

00:06:16.720 --> 00:06:20.320
Very proud that we've had as
board members and benefactors

00:06:20.320 --> 00:06:23.440
Larry and Sergey
and Eric and Ann

00:06:23.440 --> 00:06:27.340
and a multitude of Googlers
in the earliest days.

00:06:27.340 --> 00:06:33.490
And folks like Elon Musk and
Jim Cameron and Ratan Tata.

00:06:33.490 --> 00:06:35.582
And so we've launched
a bunch of prizes.

00:06:35.582 --> 00:06:37.790
I'm going to give you a few
that are active right now

00:06:37.790 --> 00:06:39.690
just for fun.

00:06:39.690 --> 00:06:42.760
Elon funded a Global
Learning XPRIZE.

00:06:42.760 --> 00:06:45.070
And we asked teams,
can you build

00:06:45.070 --> 00:06:48.910
a piece of Android
software that could

00:06:48.910 --> 00:06:51.280
take a child in the
middle of no place

00:06:51.280 --> 00:06:53.800
from illiteracy to reading,
writing, and numeracy

00:06:53.800 --> 00:06:56.120
in under 18 months?

00:06:56.120 --> 00:07:00.700
And so Sundar very kindly
gave us 5,000 Android tablets.

00:07:00.700 --> 00:07:03.060
With the World Food Programme,
we went into Tanzania,

00:07:03.060 --> 00:07:04.210
where we are right now.

00:07:04.210 --> 00:07:07.780
We interviewed
hundreds of villages.

00:07:07.780 --> 00:07:12.550
And we found 2,500 kids who
knew no Swahili and no English

00:07:12.550 --> 00:07:14.250
and put the tablets
in their hands.

00:07:14.250 --> 00:07:17.030
We had 800 teams
enter the competition.

00:07:17.030 --> 00:07:20.590
141-ish delivered software.

00:07:20.590 --> 00:07:22.180
We narrowed that
to five finalists.

00:07:22.180 --> 00:07:25.581
Those five finalists are in 500
tablets each in the villages

00:07:25.581 --> 00:07:26.080
right now.

00:07:26.080 --> 00:07:28.780
We're measuring the impact
on the child, the family,

00:07:28.780 --> 00:07:30.220
and the village.

00:07:30.220 --> 00:07:33.760
And then we're going to open
source the winning software.

00:07:33.760 --> 00:07:37.420
The goal would be that this
becomes part of Android kernel,

00:07:37.420 --> 00:07:40.270
for example, and the notion that
every time an Android device

00:07:40.270 --> 00:07:42.740
is built, it's a teacher.

00:07:42.740 --> 00:07:44.995
We're building a
billion teachers a year.

00:07:44.995 --> 00:07:48.320
We had to go in those villages
and set up power there.

00:07:48.320 --> 00:07:50.980
So that's one
XPRIZE we're doing.

00:07:50.980 --> 00:07:54.340
One that we just awarded is
called the Water Abundance

00:07:54.340 --> 00:07:56.260
XPRIZE.

00:07:56.260 --> 00:07:58.140
Half the disease
burden on planet Earth

00:07:58.140 --> 00:07:59.830
is due to unclean
drinking water.

00:07:59.830 --> 00:08:05.014
And so we asked the team,
could you pull water out

00:08:05.014 --> 00:08:07.180
of the atmosphere-- there
are quadrillions of liters

00:08:07.180 --> 00:08:09.250
of water in the atmosphere.

00:08:09.250 --> 00:08:13.090
When it condenses on
particles, we call it rain.

00:08:13.090 --> 00:08:16.090
And could you pull the water
out of the atmosphere, 2,000

00:08:16.090 --> 00:08:18.880
liters, for under
$0.02 per liter

00:08:18.880 --> 00:08:20.960
from all renewable energy?

00:08:20.960 --> 00:08:24.880
And we just awarded the
winner of that competition

00:08:24.880 --> 00:08:27.040
about a month ago.

00:08:27.040 --> 00:08:28.990
I just came back from Greece.

00:08:28.990 --> 00:08:33.856
And we have an XPRIZE
going on right now

00:08:33.856 --> 00:08:35.679
on mapping the ocean floor.

00:08:35.679 --> 00:08:38.659
We've mapped less than
5% of the ocean floor.

00:08:38.659 --> 00:08:40.909
The physics of saltwater
makes it very difficult.

00:08:40.909 --> 00:08:43.690
And so we said, to
win this prize--

00:08:43.690 --> 00:08:46.960
it's $7 million put up
by Shell and by NOAA--

00:08:46.960 --> 00:08:49.330
you've got to build an
autonomous vehicle that

00:08:49.330 --> 00:08:53.650
can launch from land, go
out some distance, tens

00:08:53.650 --> 00:08:56.000
of kilometers, into
the ocean, then go down

00:08:56.000 --> 00:09:01.660
4,000 meters and map 250
square kilometers in 24

00:09:01.660 --> 00:09:05.230
hours on its own, return,
and provide the data.

00:09:05.230 --> 00:09:08.860
So fully autonomous,
large-scale mapping.

00:09:08.860 --> 00:09:12.340
We're down to five finalists
that are in Greece right now,

00:09:12.340 --> 00:09:16.010
off the coast of the mainland.

00:09:16.010 --> 00:09:18.440
And I met two of the five teams.

00:09:18.440 --> 00:09:21.520
One team is a group
of 13 academics

00:09:21.520 --> 00:09:23.174
and grad students from Germany.

00:09:23.174 --> 00:09:25.090
Another team is two
people out of Switzerland.

00:09:25.090 --> 00:09:26.530
Another team is out of Japan.

00:09:26.530 --> 00:09:28.030
And it's amazing
what they're doing.

00:09:28.030 --> 00:09:31.332
It's transforming what's
possible in the ocean.

00:09:31.332 --> 00:09:33.040
One of my favorite
XPRIZEs going on right

00:09:33.040 --> 00:09:35.170
now is called the Avatar XPRIZE.

00:09:35.170 --> 00:09:38.380
And we asked teams to
build a robotic avatar.

00:09:38.380 --> 00:09:40.900
So a robot-- so
imagine I'm not here.

00:09:40.900 --> 00:09:43.960
I'm back in Santa
Monica, where I live.

00:09:43.960 --> 00:09:46.060
And at home, I've
got on a pair of VR

00:09:46.060 --> 00:09:48.950
goggles and a haptic suit.

00:09:48.950 --> 00:09:51.280
And as I'm moving around,
the robot's moving around.

00:09:51.280 --> 00:09:53.363
As I'm looking at you, the
robot's looking at you.

00:09:53.363 --> 00:09:58.420
So it's basically a
remote avatar telepresence

00:09:58.420 --> 00:10:02.290
to allow you to go
and solve a problem,

00:10:02.290 --> 00:10:06.220
do a medical diagnostic, go into
a disaster zone, and so forth.

00:10:06.220 --> 00:10:09.380
We've had over 400 teams
entering that competition.

00:10:09.380 --> 00:10:10.660
So a lot of XPRIZEs going on.

00:10:10.660 --> 00:10:13.750
We can dive into more
when Jack and I talk

00:10:13.750 --> 00:10:15.310
or you have your questions.

00:10:15.310 --> 00:10:18.340
Another area I'm passionate
about is human longevity.

00:10:18.340 --> 00:10:22.030
I'm clear we're going to be able
to add 10, 20, potentially 30

00:10:22.030 --> 00:10:24.820
healthy years in
everyone's life.

00:10:24.820 --> 00:10:27.880
Google's got a massive
investment in Calico.

00:10:27.880 --> 00:10:30.430
Besides Calico,
there is a multitude

00:10:30.430 --> 00:10:32.785
of different companies
going on right now.

00:10:32.785 --> 00:10:36.070
A company down in
San Diego, Samumed,

00:10:36.070 --> 00:10:38.590
that's manipulating
Wnt pathways, which

00:10:38.590 --> 00:10:40.540
is a communication pathway.

00:10:40.540 --> 00:10:43.300
That's a $13 billion
private company

00:10:43.300 --> 00:10:45.130
because their results
are extraordinary.

00:10:45.130 --> 00:10:47.110
They're in phase
2 clinical trials

00:10:47.110 --> 00:10:50.650
on a multitude of
different anti-cancer,

00:10:50.650 --> 00:10:54.640
hair growth, anti-wrinkles,
osteogenesis.

00:10:54.640 --> 00:10:57.130
I mean, it's incredible
what they're doing.

00:10:57.130 --> 00:10:59.860
You see companies like
Unity Biosciences, which

00:10:59.860 --> 00:11:01.600
are working on
senolytic medicines

00:11:01.600 --> 00:11:06.700
to kill senile cells, cells
that have grown to the Hayflick

00:11:06.700 --> 00:11:08.830
limit and have
stopped replicating

00:11:08.830 --> 00:11:11.020
and then are becoming
inflammatory agents.

00:11:11.020 --> 00:11:14.290
If you can kill those cells
and make room for new cells

00:11:14.290 --> 00:11:16.810
to generate from
endogenous stem cells,

00:11:16.810 --> 00:11:23.050
the organism regenerates and
you get an extended lifespan.

00:11:23.050 --> 00:11:26.710
Another-- I have two companies
in the longevity business.

00:11:26.710 --> 00:11:30.580
One is in the stem cell
business, called Celularity.

00:11:30.580 --> 00:11:35.800
We have the world's
largest bank of placentas.

00:11:35.800 --> 00:11:38.710
Turns out you can think of
the placenta as the 3D printer

00:11:38.710 --> 00:11:40.570
that manufactures the baby.

00:11:40.570 --> 00:11:43.990
And that placenta is the
richest source of stem cells.

00:11:43.990 --> 00:11:46.600
And so those stem
cells, delivered back

00:11:46.600 --> 00:11:51.070
to an aging organism, can
extend life 30-plus percent.

00:11:51.070 --> 00:11:54.550
As we age, our stem cells in our
bodies in all the compartments

00:11:54.550 --> 00:11:57.130
fall off very rapidly over time.

00:11:57.130 --> 00:11:58.870
And so one of the
reasons for aging

00:11:58.870 --> 00:12:01.270
is we lose the ability
to regenerate ourselves,

00:12:01.270 --> 00:12:02.590
to repair ourselves.

00:12:02.590 --> 00:12:06.550
Or the stem cells in our body,
they will drop 100x to 1,000x

00:12:06.550 --> 00:12:07.780
in population.

00:12:07.780 --> 00:12:10.510
But they undergo epigenetic
changes, mutations,

00:12:10.510 --> 00:12:14.480
and so forth, and they're not
capable as they were before.

00:12:14.480 --> 00:12:18.340
So stem cell replenishment
is another area.

00:12:18.340 --> 00:12:24.100
One fun one that I co-founded
called Human Longevity,

00:12:24.100 --> 00:12:25.840
we're down in San Diego.

00:12:25.840 --> 00:12:28.420
We'll be opening
around the country.

00:12:28.420 --> 00:12:32.980
And what Human Longevity does
is you come in for three hours,

00:12:32.980 --> 00:12:35.840
we sequence your genome--
all 3.2 billion letters.

00:12:35.840 --> 00:12:37.490
We do a 30x sequencing on you.

00:12:37.490 --> 00:12:39.250
We sequence your microbiome.

00:12:39.250 --> 00:12:42.880
We look at your metabolome,
basically the top

00:12:42.880 --> 00:12:47.590
100-plus proteins and
chemicals and small molecules

00:12:47.590 --> 00:12:48.700
in your bloodstream.

00:12:48.700 --> 00:12:51.880
We do a full body MRI,
head to toe, a brain MRI,

00:12:51.880 --> 00:12:55.300
brain vasculature,
coronary CT, lung CT.

00:12:55.300 --> 00:12:57.790
And then we feed about
150 gigabytes of data

00:12:57.790 --> 00:13:01.040
into our system to
determine two things.

00:13:01.040 --> 00:13:03.460
Number one, is there anything
going on inside your body

00:13:03.460 --> 00:13:05.680
right now that you
should know about?

00:13:05.680 --> 00:13:08.290
And number two, based
upon your genetics,

00:13:08.290 --> 00:13:12.590
what are you likely to die from,
and how do you find it before?

00:13:12.590 --> 00:13:14.350
So the numbers are
pretty telling.

00:13:14.350 --> 00:13:17.445
The price point
initially for HLI--

00:13:17.445 --> 00:13:18.820
what's called the
health nucleus,

00:13:18.820 --> 00:13:20.921
the facility-- was $25,000.

00:13:20.921 --> 00:13:21.670
So it's not cheap.

00:13:21.670 --> 00:13:26.540
All these people who came
were very well-to-do patients,

00:13:26.540 --> 00:13:28.420
so to speak.

00:13:28.420 --> 00:13:31.120
The price has dropped
down to $5,000 and $3,000

00:13:31.120 --> 00:13:32.140
for subsequent visits.

00:13:32.140 --> 00:13:35.950
But still, in 2%--

00:13:35.950 --> 00:13:38.380
so we're in a room
of roughly 100.

00:13:38.380 --> 00:13:41.470
Two of you have a brain
or aortic aneurysm

00:13:41.470 --> 00:13:43.660
you don't know about,
which is kind of shocking.

00:13:43.660 --> 00:13:47.470
2%-- and this is for populations
older than you are here, for 50

00:13:47.470 --> 00:13:49.606
and older--

00:13:49.606 --> 00:13:52.420
have a high-grade cancer tumor.

00:13:52.420 --> 00:13:57.100
3.4% have a significant cardiac
condition-- atrial fibrillation

00:13:57.100 --> 00:14:00.360
or a bundle branch
block or [INAUDIBLE]..

00:14:00.360 --> 00:14:03.070
And we find 14% of the
people who come through

00:14:03.070 --> 00:14:06.410
have significant findings they
take action on immediately.

00:14:06.410 --> 00:14:08.830
So the fact of the matter
is we're all optimists.

00:14:08.830 --> 00:14:11.200
We think everything's
fine in our body.

00:14:11.200 --> 00:14:13.540
And then, until you go to
the hospital, at which point

00:14:13.540 --> 00:14:15.580
you're like, oh shit.

00:14:15.580 --> 00:14:17.050
I didn't know that.

00:14:17.050 --> 00:14:18.079
But I'm a pilot.

00:14:18.079 --> 00:14:19.120
I fly a couple of planes.

00:14:19.120 --> 00:14:22.120
Before I take off, make sure
everything's in the green.

00:14:22.120 --> 00:14:23.770
But for most of us,
we don't know that.

00:14:23.770 --> 00:14:25.270
Eventually we'll
all have wearables.

00:14:25.270 --> 00:14:27.820
We were talking about, I
have my Oura ring here,

00:14:27.820 --> 00:14:31.180
with about 14, 15
different sensors that

00:14:31.180 --> 00:14:34.060
measure my pulse wave form, my
temperature, my acceleration,

00:14:34.060 --> 00:14:36.640
and give me sleep data.

00:14:36.640 --> 00:14:38.230
I've got my Apple Watch.

00:14:38.230 --> 00:14:43.150
I've got a small little RFID
chip implanted over here.

00:14:43.150 --> 00:14:46.150
It's got my business card on it.

00:14:46.150 --> 00:14:47.920
Completely useless,
but eventually it'll

00:14:47.920 --> 00:14:49.570
be something useful.

00:14:49.570 --> 00:14:51.670
But we'll all have
this data uploaded

00:14:51.670 --> 00:14:54.494
to give us minute by
minute how are we doing.

00:14:54.494 --> 00:14:55.910
And the goal--
people say, I don't

00:14:55.910 --> 00:14:57.040
want to know if
anything's wrong with me.

00:14:57.040 --> 00:14:57.539
Bullshit.

00:14:57.539 --> 00:14:58.950
Of course you want to know.

00:14:58.950 --> 00:15:02.080
And you want to solve it right
then at the very beginning,

00:15:02.080 --> 00:15:03.684
when it's most solvable.

00:15:03.684 --> 00:15:06.100
So it's going from sick care,
which is what is right now--

00:15:06.100 --> 00:15:08.050
we take care of you
after you're sick--

00:15:08.050 --> 00:15:11.620
to health care, to find
anything at stage zero.

00:15:11.620 --> 00:15:13.660
So I'll close.

