00:21:20.230 --> 00:21:22.980
was about $3 billion, went
down to $100 million, hit

00:21:22.980 --> 00:21:24.691
$1,000, now about $500.

00:21:24.691 --> 00:21:26.190
And as you mentioned,
probably we're

00:21:26.190 --> 00:21:29.430
on the way to $100 or even less.

00:21:29.430 --> 00:21:31.020
And of course, the
analysis with that

00:21:31.020 --> 00:21:32.910
is as important as
the sequencing itself.

00:21:32.910 --> 00:21:36.840
And that's starting to ramp up
the bioinformatics around it.

00:21:36.840 --> 00:21:39.030
Estimates are that
right now, in total--

00:21:39.030 --> 00:21:41.010
putting aside smaller
genomic tests,

00:21:41.010 --> 00:21:43.110
but in terms of whole
genome sequencing--

00:21:43.110 --> 00:21:45.020
there maybe are a
few hundred thousand,

00:21:45.020 --> 00:21:46.920
maximum a million
people, who maybe have--

00:21:46.920 --> 00:21:48.900
out of 7-plus billion people.

00:21:48.900 --> 00:21:51.030
When do we get to a
critical mass that

00:21:51.030 --> 00:21:54.720
helps us understand the
significance of billions

00:21:54.720 --> 00:21:57.600
of those base pairs that
we don't understand yet

00:21:57.600 --> 00:21:58.890
the sequence significance of?

00:21:58.890 --> 00:22:03.270
In other words, we have a lot of
good sense about the usual 500

00:22:03.270 --> 00:22:05.790
that are cancer drivers,
that are oncogenes.

00:22:05.790 --> 00:22:08.910
We don't have a good sense
of literally billions-plus

00:22:08.910 --> 00:22:11.820
of some of those base
pairs in sequence.

00:22:11.820 --> 00:22:13.530
Tell us about the
critical mass we

00:22:13.530 --> 00:22:15.870
need to start to
understand the sample size

00:22:15.870 --> 00:22:17.670
that we need to really
draw conclusions.

00:22:17.670 --> 00:22:20.250
PETER DIAMANDIS: So we're
getting amazing results

00:22:20.250 --> 00:22:24.860
with tens of thousands
right now at HLI.

00:22:24.860 --> 00:22:27.695
I can't state this stuff
until it's published.

00:22:27.695 --> 00:22:32.040
But traditionally we
talk about the exome,

00:22:32.040 --> 00:22:35.340
the part of the genome
that codes for proteins.

00:22:35.340 --> 00:22:37.290
And yes, it has been
euphemistically called

00:22:37.290 --> 00:22:38.700
junk DNA.

00:22:38.700 --> 00:22:40.080
But it's not junk DNA.

00:22:40.080 --> 00:22:41.340
None of it's junk DNA.

00:22:41.340 --> 00:22:45.180
It's all, in some way,
structural or coding or control

00:22:45.180 --> 00:22:45.720
segments.

00:22:45.720 --> 00:22:48.090
And it's interesting
that as you look

00:22:48.090 --> 00:22:49.920
at a large-enough
population, you

00:22:49.920 --> 00:22:54.570
start to say, listen, these
segments of DNA are protective.

00:22:54.570 --> 00:22:58.080
Any mutation here is
lethal to the person.

00:22:58.080 --> 00:23:00.990
So we start to
discover by elimination

00:23:00.990 --> 00:23:04.500
and by subtraction fascinating
parts of the genome that

00:23:04.500 --> 00:23:05.790
are worth looking at.

00:23:05.790 --> 00:23:08.880
And the other thing I might just
say is it's the correlation.

00:23:08.880 --> 00:23:10.860
What was real exciting
is the correlation

00:23:10.860 --> 00:23:14.790
between genome and then rich
phenotypic data, when we've

00:23:14.790 --> 00:23:18.030
got your genome and then
we have full-body MRI

00:23:18.030 --> 00:23:21.090
and coronary and heart CT
and metabolome and so forth.

00:23:21.090 --> 00:23:23.820
Then you start to
really correlate, aha,

00:23:23.820 --> 00:23:24.829
that's what this does.

00:23:24.829 --> 00:23:25.620
JACK HIDARY: Right.

00:23:25.620 --> 00:23:27.060
And I was going to
get to methylation.

00:23:27.060 --> 00:23:28.770
Right now, genome
sequence is coming down.

00:23:28.770 --> 00:23:30.360
But the ability to
get to epigenetics,

00:23:30.360 --> 00:23:32.332
in terms of methyl
groups, things like that,

00:23:32.332 --> 00:23:34.290
talk to us about all the
other rich information

00:23:34.290 --> 00:23:36.430
that's necessary to really
draw those conclusions.

00:23:36.430 --> 00:23:39.480
PETER DIAMANDIS: So I think
one of the things that is true

00:23:39.480 --> 00:23:41.940
is this next decade
