Sharks could live
400 or 500 years.

00:24:16.290 --> 00:24:18.060
Turtles could 600, 700 years.

00:24:18.060 --> 00:24:21.030
And I was like, if
they can, why can't we?

00:24:21.030 --> 00:24:23.359
It's either a software
problem or a hardware problem.

00:24:23.359 --> 00:24:24.900
JACK HIDARY: Or we
need to swim more.

00:24:24.900 --> 00:24:26.941
PETER DIAMANDIS: We have
to be in the water more,

00:24:26.941 --> 00:24:28.817
cool our body temperatures down.

00:24:28.817 --> 00:24:30.900
But I really think we're
going to start to unravel

00:24:30.900 --> 00:24:32.100
that and understand it.

00:24:32.100 --> 00:24:34.308
JACK HIDARY: And let's jump
to another area of health

00:24:34.308 --> 00:24:35.400
care, which is our brains.

00:24:35.400 --> 00:24:37.316
You mentioned that we're
going to live longer,

00:24:37.316 --> 00:24:40.090
and it's already happening
in a number of countries.

00:24:40.090 --> 00:24:42.810
But that also now is
revealing greater populations

00:24:42.810 --> 00:24:46.140
with Alzheimer's, Parkinson's,
neurological diseases.

00:24:46.140 --> 00:24:50.190
We've had a good handle so
far on cardiac diseases.

00:24:50.190 --> 00:24:53.310
Morbidity from cardiac
has actually come down.

00:24:53.310 --> 00:24:57.300
Diabetes is on the rise, but
there's some hopes there.

00:24:57.300 --> 00:24:59.250
But talk about the
neurological diseases.

00:24:59.250 --> 00:25:03.390
PETER DIAMANDIS: Yeah, so
we have cardiac conditions

00:25:03.390 --> 00:25:04.840
in our 50s and 60s.

00:25:04.840 --> 00:25:07.440
We have cancers in
our 60s and 70s.

00:25:07.440 --> 00:25:10.290
And we have neurological
disease in our 70s and 80s.

00:25:10.290 --> 00:25:12.620
And the fact of the matter
is just for context--

00:25:12.620 --> 00:25:14.286
JACK HIDARY: Now
that's a bright future.

00:25:14.286 --> 00:25:15.180
I like that.

00:25:15.180 --> 00:25:17.055
PETER DIAMANDIS: Until
you prevent it, right?

00:25:17.055 --> 00:25:19.200
Life is short until you
extend it, and so forth.

00:25:19.200 --> 00:25:24.701
But the human body was never
intended to live past age 30.

00:25:24.701 --> 00:25:26.700
I mean, just to put it
on the table here, right?

00:25:26.700 --> 00:25:29.550
You would go into
puberty at age 13.

00:25:29.550 --> 00:25:31.390
You'd have a baby.

00:25:31.390 --> 00:25:33.160
And then by the
time you were 26,

00:25:33.160 --> 00:25:34.990
your baby was having a baby.

00:25:34.990 --> 00:25:37.300
And back then,
100,000 years ago,

00:25:37.300 --> 00:25:39.970
before Whole Foods and
McDonald's was around,

00:25:39.970 --> 00:25:42.179
when food was scarce,
the last thing

00:25:42.179 --> 00:25:43.720
you wanted to do
for the selfish gene

00:25:43.720 --> 00:25:47.150
was to take the money out of
your grandchildren's mouths

00:25:47.150 --> 00:25:48.590
and now compete with them.

00:25:48.590 --> 00:25:51.173
So you would do the best thing
you could-- give your bits back

00:25:51.173 --> 00:25:52.130
to the environment.

00:25:52.130 --> 00:25:54.580
But of course,
that's changed now.

00:25:54.580 --> 00:25:56.440
And we're beginning
to extend life.

00:25:56.440 --> 00:26:00.040
And as we extend life,
we run into new problems.

00:26:00.040 --> 00:26:06.570
There is amazing drugs in phase
2 clinical trials right now.

00:26:06.570 --> 00:26:09.300
We're seeing impact from
senolytic medicines.

00:26:09.300 --> 00:26:12.390
We're seeing impacts from
Wnt pathway manipulations

00:26:12.390 --> 00:26:18.240
on cancers and Alzheimer's.

00:26:18.240 --> 00:26:21.480
I think one of the areas that
is super-exciting as well

00:26:21.480 --> 00:26:24.120
is the whole field of
brain computer interface.

00:26:24.120 --> 00:26:26.370
My last count, there's
probably $1 billion a year

00:26:26.370 --> 00:26:30.780
going into interfacing your
neocortex with the cloud

00:26:30.780 --> 00:26:33.130
in buildings not far from here.

00:26:33.130 --> 00:26:35.070
And so at the end
of the day, we're

00:26:35.070 --> 00:26:38.640
going to learn a lot about how
the brain works and the root

00:26:38.640 --> 00:26:41.645
causes of these diseases, as
we have over and over again.

00:26:41.645 --> 00:26:43.770
But a lot of it's going to
come because our ability

00:26:43.770 --> 00:26:47.130
to sense and gather data
and analyze the data

00:26:47.130 --> 00:26:53.574
is billions, trillions of
times better than ever.

00:26:53.574 --> 00:26:56.115
JACK HIDARY: Let's turn to one
of your first passions, space.

00:26:58.670 --> 00:27:01.260
Let's talk about
really space travel.

00:27:01.260 --> 00:27:04.170
We hear from Branson
that it may be imminent.

00:27:04.170 --> 00:27:06.000
Virgin Galactic may be
launching imminently

00:27:06.000 --> 00:27:06.992
with paying customers.

00:27:06.992 --> 00:27:08.700
And there's been a
long line of thousands

00:27:08.700 --> 00:27:12.090
of people putting their bets
in terms of their down payments

00:27:12.090 --> 00:27:15.665
on getting a seat on that ride,
which it's great to see that.

00:27:15.665 --> 00:27:17.790
PETER DIAMANDIS: Any Virgin
Galactic ticket holders

00:27:17.790 --> 00:27:19.670
here in the audience,
out of curiosity?

00:27:19.670 --> 00:27:21.219
I am.

00:27:21.219 --> 00:27:22.510
Lots of customers, potentially.

00:27:22.510 --> 00:27:23.384
JACK HIDARY: Exactly.

00:27:23.384 --> 00:27:26.140
PETER DIAMANDIS: I'll
take checks later.

00:27:26.140 --> 00:27:28.980
JACK HIDARY: But talk to us
about what you see as the odds

00:27:28.980 --> 00:27:30.990
that we're going to be
a multiplanet species

00:27:30.990 --> 00:27:34.950
within, say, 10 years,
20 years, 50 years.

00:27:34.950 --> 00:27:37.300
We obviously have the
potential, the technology.

00:27:37.300 --> 00:27:39.450
I don't think there's
doubt that we can actually

00:27:39.450 --> 00:27:41.140
get to another planet now.

00:27:41.140 --> 00:27:44.250
But talk to us about the
will and the mobilization

00:27:44.250 --> 00:27:45.820
to make that happen.

00:27:45.820 --> 00:27:50.550
PETER DIAMANDIS: So probably
the single most important driver

00:27:50.550 --> 00:27:57.540
that's making that happen is the
individual, passionate actor,

00:27:57.540 --> 00:28:02.310
in this case in the form of Elon
Musk and Jeff Bezos and Richard

00:28:02.310 --> 00:28:05.490
Branson and-- just passed--

00:28:05.490 --> 00:28:06.505
Paul Allen.

00:28:06.505 --> 00:28:07.380
And it's interesting.

00:28:07.380 --> 00:28:10.244
A lot of these individuals
grew up-- in the case of Jeff,

00:28:10.244 --> 00:28:12.660
who I've known for 35 years,
since the early days of SEDS.

00:28:12.660 --> 00:28:17.835
I was a founder of SEDS, and
Jeff ran the Princeton chapter.

00:28:17.835 --> 00:28:20.130
And I remember meeting Jeff
after he started Amazon.

00:28:20.130 --> 00:28:22.660
I said, what are you doing
with this Amazon thing?

00:28:22.660 --> 00:28:24.618
He goes, well, I'm going
to make a lot of money

00:28:24.618 --> 00:28:25.900
there and spend it on space.

00:28:25.900 --> 00:28:26.400
No shit.

00:28:26.400 --> 00:28:27.090
Really.

00:28:27.090 --> 00:28:30.510
And Elon's committed-- said
I will spend all his money

00:28:30.510 --> 00:28:31.920
on opening up space.

00:28:31.920 --> 00:28:33.860
Both of them are that committed.

00:28:33.860 --> 00:28:36.600
And I think a lot
of it was those

00:28:36.600 --> 00:28:40.770
who were born during the Apollo
and shuttle era got enamored

00:28:40.770 --> 00:28:44.244
with this vision, from "Star
Wars" and "Star Trek" and all

00:28:44.244 --> 00:28:44.910
of those things.

00:28:44.910 --> 00:28:47.940
And then NASA never implemented.

00:28:47.940 --> 00:28:50.760
It never paid off on the deal.

00:28:50.760 --> 00:28:53.430
And so now you've got
individuals saying,

00:28:53.430 --> 00:28:56.040
we'll do it.

00:28:56.040 --> 00:28:59.250
I've known Elon since he
sold PayPal and watched

00:28:59.250 --> 00:29:02.910
what he did with SpaceX,
with the Falcon 1

00:29:02.910 --> 00:29:04.560
and 1e and Falcon 9 and Heavy.

00:29:04.560 --> 00:29:06.300
And I would never
bet against him.

00:29:06.300 --> 00:29:08.860
He is dead set on
making that happen.

00:29:08.860 --> 00:29:10.680
And I think he will.

00:29:10.680 --> 00:29:15.000
He set a target at landing in
2024 on the Martian surface.

00:29:15.000 --> 00:29:18.120
OK, listen, I'll give
him an extra four years.

00:29:18.120 --> 00:29:20.730
But could he get there by 2028?

00:29:20.730 --> 00:29:24.750
I would bet on him over
any government, hands down.

00:29:24.750 --> 00:29:29.760
And then Jeff is sort of
the tortoise in the race.

00:29:29.760 --> 00:29:31.500
He's committed $1
billion a year.

00:29:31.500 --> 00:29:35.860
And he's just--
that is his endgame.

00:29:35.860 --> 00:29:39.090
And so I think we're
going to do it.

00:29:39.090 --> 00:29:42.980
I think it's going
to be a function of--

00:29:42.980 --> 00:29:46.320
I don't think governments
can take the risks anymore

00:29:46.320 --> 00:29:49.410
that were inherent in the
early Apollo program days.

00:29:49.410 --> 00:29:52.750
It's way too-- failure is
not an option for them,

00:29:52.750 --> 00:29:54.870
and therefore risk
is no option either.

00:29:54.870 --> 00:29:59.670
But individuals can say,
I'm going to do this.

00:29:59.670 --> 00:30:06.510
I mean, there is a Tesla
on a Earth asteroid.

00:30:06.510 --> 00:30:07.830
That's insane.

00:30:07.830 --> 00:30:09.940
I mean, just like, game over.

00:30:09.940 --> 00:30:10.690
Proof point.

00:30:10.690 --> 00:30:12.427
JACK HIDARY: Yeah.

00:30:12.427 --> 00:30:14.260
You mention a number
of great entrepreneurs,

00:30:14.260 --> 00:30:16.176
and we can see how they're
changing the world.

00:30:16.176 --> 00:30:17.907
So let's talk about
entrepreneurship now.

00:30:17.907 --> 00:30:20.490
Here in Silicon Valley, we know
the power of entrepreneurship.

00:30:20.490 --> 00:30:20.990
We see it.

00:30:20.990 --> 00:30:21.592
We feel it.

00:30:21.592 --> 00:30:23.300
There's other key
entrepreneurial centers

00:30:23.300 --> 00:30:24.120
around the world.

00:30:24.120 --> 00:30:26.450
But it's not spread
evenly enough yet.

00:30:26.450 --> 00:30:29.420
It's not as inclusive as it
needs to be and could be.

00:30:29.420 --> 00:30:31.160
And not only is
that the case, we're

00:30:31.160 --> 00:30:33.080
missing out on the
talents of many

00:30:33.080 --> 00:30:35.240
of those people from
diverse backgrounds

00:30:35.240 --> 00:30:38.650
that could be part of
the entrepreneurial lift

00:30:38.650 --> 00:30:39.680
and journey.

00:30:39.680 --> 00:30:42.570
What are your thoughts around
how to change that game?

00:30:42.570 --> 00:30:44.480
PETER DIAMANDIS: So
first of all, we're

00:30:44.480 --> 00:30:51.110
dematerializing, democratizing,
and demonetizing all the tools

00:30:51.110 --> 00:30:53.090
for entrepreneurship.

00:30:53.090 --> 00:30:57.060
So it used to be that
to be an entrepreneur,

00:30:57.060 --> 00:30:59.080
you needed to have
computational power.

00:30:59.080 --> 00:31:02.430
You needed to have an
ethernet cable or a modem plug

00:31:02.430 --> 00:31:03.290
or whatever.

00:31:03.290 --> 00:31:04.940
And you needed to have--

00:31:04.940 --> 00:31:08.090
now, obviously with
Google Cloud and AWS,

00:31:08.090 --> 00:31:11.840
you have all the
computational power you want.

00:31:11.840 --> 00:31:15.350
The number is by
2023, I believe,

00:31:15.350 --> 00:31:19.560
there'll be $300 billion
available in crowdfunding,

00:31:19.560 --> 00:31:22.070
which means anyone around
the world with a good idea

00:31:22.070 --> 00:31:24.710
can launch a crowdfunding
campaign to get the capital.

00:31:24.710 --> 00:31:28.130
So capital becomes
less of a restriction.

00:31:28.130 --> 00:31:30.780
Obviously, Google makes the
world's information available.

00:31:30.780 --> 00:31:35.210
So what used to be
scarce resources--

00:31:35.210 --> 00:31:37.730
I mean, bandwidth, I
remember back in 2001,

00:31:37.730 --> 00:31:40.370
I had a stealth company
called Blastoff.

00:31:40.370 --> 00:31:43.250
My number-one expense
was Akamai on bandwidth

00:31:43.250 --> 00:31:44.310
to send video to people.

00:31:44.310 --> 00:31:45.360
It was ridiculous.

00:31:45.360 --> 00:31:47.390
And now it's nothing.

00:31:47.390 --> 00:31:51.815
So literally everything
you need to be

00:31:51.815 --> 00:31:54.530
to create an
entrepreneurial startup

00:31:54.530 --> 00:31:59.630
is becoming available globally
at lower and lower costs.

00:31:59.630 --> 00:32:04.430
And so it's now, the
number-one scarce resource

00:32:04.430 --> 00:32:07.880
that I see in entrepreneurship
around the world is mindset.

00:32:07.880 --> 00:32:12.950
So I was just in Greece
at an SU Athens summit,

00:32:12.950 --> 00:32:16.850
meeting there with heads of the
country and the entrepreneurs.

00:32:16.850 --> 00:32:19.700
And they were saying,
what do we need to do

00:32:19.700 --> 00:32:21.530
to become more innovative?

00:32:21.530 --> 00:32:23.990
It's a country of
10 million people.

00:32:23.990 --> 00:32:28.850
It's like one Google-size
success story dwarfs

00:32:28.850 --> 00:32:30.690
the budget of the country.

00:32:30.690 --> 00:32:34.940
So it's like you need to create
a mindset of entrepreneurship.

00:32:34.940 --> 00:32:35.690
You need to have--

00:32:35.690 --> 00:32:37.350
some venture capital
would be great.

00:32:37.350 --> 00:32:40.400
But failure needs
to be an option.

00:32:40.400 --> 00:32:43.160
So a lot of Central and
South American countries,

00:32:43.160 --> 00:32:46.220
if you fail, it's a
black mark for life.

00:32:46.220 --> 00:32:48.140
Here we call it success.

00:32:48.140 --> 00:32:50.330
At X, you celebrate
a failure every week

00:32:50.330 --> 00:32:52.307
when someone gives
up their company

00:32:52.307 --> 00:32:53.890
and say we're going
to spend our money

00:32:53.890 --> 00:32:55.520
and our time
someplace else better.

00:32:55.520 --> 00:32:56.240
That's amazing.

00:32:56.240 --> 00:33:00.077
So it's teaching that
mindset of failure.

00:33:00.077 --> 00:33:01.910
I had this conversation
with Ratan Tata, one

00:33:01.910 --> 00:33:04.490
of our fellow trustees, who--

00:33:04.490 --> 00:33:06.170
in India, it's really hard.

00:33:06.170 --> 00:33:08.550
If you fail, you're screwed.

00:33:08.550 --> 00:33:11.390
And so you don't take big steps.

00:33:11.390 --> 00:33:14.750
And so he wanted to sort
of dismiss that ethos.

00:33:14.750 --> 00:33:17.690
And so he was like, we're
going to celebrate failure.

00:33:17.690 --> 00:33:19.580
We're going to celebrate
a great idea that

00:33:19.580 --> 00:33:22.100
was worth trying
that failed and give

00:33:22.100 --> 00:33:23.469
this person their next shot.

00:33:23.469 --> 00:33:25.760
JACK HIDARY: So speaking of
that mindset breakthrough--

00:33:25.760 --> 00:33:27.593
and then we'll turn to
one or two questions.

00:33:27.593 --> 00:33:30.597
So if you want to line up at the
mike, if people have questions.

00:33:33.120 --> 00:33:34.957
You've now-- [INAUDIBLE]
has now trained,

00:33:34.957 --> 00:33:37.040
I don't know, thousands
of people, it must be now,

00:33:37.040 --> 00:33:38.190
in exponential thinking.

00:33:38.190 --> 00:33:39.731
And through XPRIZE
and others, you've

00:33:39.731 --> 00:33:41.690
also touched a lot
of people and changed

00:33:41.690 --> 00:33:45.610
a lot of people's mindset
about what is possible.

00:33:45.610 --> 00:33:47.780
When you go back
to the news reports

00:33:47.780 --> 00:33:50.477
on polio back in the early
part of the last century,

00:33:50.477 --> 00:33:52.310
it's written in such a
way that people never

00:33:52.310 --> 00:33:54.590
thought it could be overcome.

00:33:54.590 --> 00:33:56.750
Today, when people
speak about cancer,

00:33:56.750 --> 00:33:58.640
yes, incremental progress.

00:33:58.640 --> 00:34:00.622
But most people,
when you ask them,

00:34:00.622 --> 00:34:02.330
they don't believe
that in their lifetime

00:34:02.330 --> 00:34:04.040
we're going to
see the management

00:34:04.040 --> 00:34:05.930
and containment of cancer.

00:34:05.930 --> 00:34:08.540
So identify for us
three or four things

00:34:08.540 --> 00:34:09.980
that you think we should apply--

00:34:09.980 --> 00:34:12.199
exponential breakthrough
thinking-- and we're

00:34:12.199 --> 00:34:13.010
not doing today.

00:34:13.010 --> 00:34:15.739
And we're going to look back
30, 40 years from now and say,

00:34:15.739 --> 00:34:19.787
we were people like polio,
looking at polio the same way.

00:34:19.787 --> 00:34:21.620
That we should have had
a different mindset.

00:34:21.620 --> 00:34:21.980
PETER DIAMANDIS: Sure.

00:34:21.980 --> 00:34:23.521
So let me talk about
where the places

00:34:23.521 --> 00:34:26.719
we're doing XPRIZEs
as a perfect example.

00:34:26.719 --> 00:34:30.560
So first of all, we
are in final steps

00:34:30.560 --> 00:34:32.600
for what I hope will
be a $100 million

00:34:32.600 --> 00:34:36.530
cancer XPRIZE for going beyond
liquid biopsy, but very early

00:34:36.530 --> 00:34:38.870
detection.

00:34:38.870 --> 00:34:42.949
Something like a blood test,
or something like a Pap smear,

00:34:42.949 --> 00:34:45.199
or something that
is tens of dollars,

00:34:45.199 --> 00:34:48.199
very easy to do
type of detection.

00:34:48.199 --> 00:34:51.590
We're also working on an
Alzheimer's XPRIZE, same order

00:34:51.590 --> 00:34:53.030
of magnitude.

00:34:53.030 --> 00:34:55.370
One of my favorite prizes
that I want to do right now

00:34:55.370 --> 00:34:58.460
is a fire detection
and extinction XPRIZE.

00:34:58.460 --> 00:35:03.840
The idea that we don't know when
a fire starts is ridiculous.

00:35:03.840 --> 00:35:07.380
So this is a simple
XPRIZE for me.

00:35:07.380 --> 00:35:11.310
A team is given 500 square
kilometers of forest land.

00:35:11.310 --> 00:35:15.210
And you have to detect a fire
above a certain lumen level--

00:35:15.210 --> 00:35:17.870
let's say five campfires' worth.

00:35:17.870 --> 00:35:20.520
And you have to put it
out within 10 minutes.

00:35:20.520 --> 00:35:22.420
And I don't care how
you do it-- with drones,

00:35:22.420 --> 00:35:24.420
with water balloons,
whatever the case might be.

00:35:24.420 --> 00:35:28.440
I think if that
technology exists,

00:35:28.440 --> 00:35:32.340
insurance makes it
possible and deploys it

00:35:32.340 --> 00:35:33.540
across all forest lands.

00:35:33.540 --> 00:35:35.760
We don't have devastating
forest fires again.

00:35:35.760 --> 00:35:37.950
So I'd love to do that.

00:35:37.950 --> 00:35:42.150
Working on a earthquake
prediction XPRIZE, I think,

00:35:42.150 --> 00:35:44.280
is a massive data play.

00:35:44.280 --> 00:35:47.910
There's no way in the world
that a magnitude 6 earthquake

00:35:47.910 --> 00:35:52.980
doesn't leave digital
trails before it unleashes

00:35:52.980 --> 00:35:55.830
30 Hiroshima bombs of energy.

00:35:55.830 --> 00:36:01.950
Working on a hurricane
trajectory prediction XPRIZE.

00:36:01.950 --> 00:36:08.550
So it turns out that all
those wide-area projections

00:36:08.550 --> 00:36:11.100
of a hurricane
cause devastation.

00:36:11.100 --> 00:36:13.020
And if you can
measure wind velocity

00:36:13.020 --> 00:36:17.370
at 10 meters above the center
of the eye of a hurricane,

00:36:17.370 --> 00:36:18.580
that's the missing data.

00:36:18.580 --> 00:36:20.850
So is there a drone
or a technology

00:36:20.850 --> 00:36:23.220
for doing that accurately?

00:36:23.220 --> 00:36:24.420
There's energy XPRIZE.

00:36:24.420 --> 00:36:27.210
We're working on a feeding
the next billion XPRIZE

00:36:27.210 --> 00:36:30.840
for massive protein
food production.

00:36:30.840 --> 00:36:33.900
The way that we grow
our protein today--

00:36:33.900 --> 00:36:37.770
this is a planet for
cows, if you didn't know.

00:36:37.770 --> 00:36:40.920
One-third of our non-ice
landmass is used--

00:36:40.920 --> 00:36:46.590
hey, Peter-- is used for
livestock production.

00:36:46.590 --> 00:36:50.860
And that's crazy, with CO2,
water, energy, and so forth.

00:36:50.860 --> 00:36:54.600
So we've been working with
a lot of the companies that

00:36:54.600 --> 00:36:56.580
are in the beginning
of cultured meat

00:36:56.580 --> 00:37:03.660
to create a large-scale cultured
meat XPRIZE for stem cell

00:37:03.660 --> 00:37:05.840
meat and plant-based
derivative that tastes

00:37:05.840 --> 00:37:07.452
better than what you buy.

00:37:07.452 --> 00:37:08.910
JACK HIDARY: And
I guess finally, I

00:37:08.910 --> 00:37:11.010
know you've been thinking about
housing for a while, in terms

00:37:11.010 --> 00:37:13.230
of the ability to-- not
necessarily from an XPRIZE--

00:37:13.230 --> 00:37:16.240
but in general, could we
provide housing for folks.

00:37:16.240 --> 00:37:18.230
So with that, we have
time for two questions.

00:37:18.230 --> 00:37:19.020
And we have two questioners.

00:37:19.020 --> 00:37:20.520
AUDIENCE: Most of
these XPRIZEs have

00:37:20.520 --> 00:37:24.120
to do with science
and technology.

00:37:24.120 --> 00:37:26.030
Or when they
involve humans, they

00:37:26.030 --> 00:37:28.320
treat humans as
individual units.

00:37:28.320 --> 00:37:30.630
How would you do an
XPRIZE that involves

00:37:30.630 --> 00:37:35.869
connections between humans
in the social space?

00:37:35.869 --> 00:37:36.660
What would they be?

00:37:36.660 --> 00:37:38.118
JACK HIDARY: Groups
of people, or--

00:37:38.118 --> 00:37:40.260
PETER DIAMANDIS: You
mean behavioral prizes?

00:37:40.260 --> 00:37:41.130
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:37:41.130 --> 00:37:42.046
PETER DIAMANDIS: Yeah.

00:37:42.046 --> 00:37:45.900
So to be clear, XPRIZEs
that have been successful

00:37:45.900 --> 00:37:49.830
so far have been for widgets,
devices, transportation modes,

00:37:49.830 --> 00:37:51.720
and things like
that, where people

00:37:51.720 --> 00:37:53.850
can go and have a very
clear, measurable objective

00:37:53.850 --> 00:37:55.560
and can rapidly iterate.

00:37:55.560 --> 00:37:57.720
We've talked about
doing competitions

00:37:57.720 --> 00:38:02.610
between regions, like cities
or companies and so forth.

00:38:02.610 --> 00:38:04.057
One my favorite XPRIZE ideas--

00:38:04.057 --> 00:38:06.390
and actually, the very first
person to ever mention this

00:38:06.390 --> 00:38:07.590
was Larry Page--

00:38:07.590 --> 00:38:09.650
would be a-- it's
a two-part prize.

00:38:09.650 --> 00:38:12.150
One would be a happiness X--
it's called a Happiness XPRIZE.

00:38:12.150 --> 00:38:15.930
Could you build a device that
could physiologically measure

00:38:15.930 --> 00:38:17.326
your state of happiness?

00:38:17.326 --> 00:38:19.200
Like if I asked you
right now, are you happy?

00:38:19.200 --> 00:38:20.610
Ah, I'm a 7.

00:38:20.610 --> 00:38:24.180
And other times I'd be a
10 or a 2, whatever it is.

00:38:24.180 --> 00:38:26.820
But if you could actually
accurately measure,

00:38:26.820 --> 00:38:30.330
then you could create a
policy change at Google

00:38:30.330 --> 00:38:33.120
and then measure did it
make people happy or not.

00:38:33.120 --> 00:38:35.460
So I think the ability
to measure something

00:38:35.460 --> 00:38:39.540
first and then create
state changes afterwards

00:38:39.540 --> 00:38:42.500
would be my approach to that.

00:38:42.500 --> 00:38:44.190
But we haven't done
it successfully yet.

00:38:44.190 --> 00:38:46.523
We keep on banging our heads
against it and continue to.

00:38:46.523 --> 00:38:47.482
But thank you for that.

00:38:47.482 --> 00:38:49.897
AUDIENCE: You talked a lot
about accelerating technologies

00:38:49.897 --> 00:38:51.130
in the near-term future.

00:38:51.130 --> 00:38:52.936
And my question had
to do with, do you

00:38:52.936 --> 00:38:55.560
think there's any risk of these
accelerating technologies being

00:38:55.560 --> 00:38:58.169
misused by bad actors in
the short or near term?

00:38:58.169 --> 00:39:00.210
I'm thinking of things
like China's social credit

00:39:00.210 --> 00:39:01.877
system, which just
seems kind of like,

00:39:01.877 --> 00:39:03.210
I don't know, a nightmare to me.

00:39:03.210 --> 00:39:05.620
But what are your
thoughts on that?

00:39:05.620 --> 00:39:08.250
PETER DIAMANDIS: So the
answer is of course.

00:39:08.250 --> 00:39:11.220
And I would just say, listen,
the social credit system--

00:39:11.220 --> 00:39:13.260
first of all, anybody
who went through school

00:39:13.260 --> 00:39:16.440
and got an A, a B, or
a C or had a review,

00:39:16.440 --> 00:39:18.340
we've had that all
through our lives.

00:39:18.340 --> 00:39:21.130
It's the negative externalities
that are the issue with that.

00:39:21.130 --> 00:39:23.490
But being able to tell
a person how-- there's

00:39:23.490 --> 00:39:26.790
good parts of a social credit
system, if it's for the upside,

00:39:26.790 --> 00:39:28.435
not for the downside.

00:39:28.435 --> 00:39:30.810
Just to be clear, not to defend
what they're doing there,

00:39:30.810 --> 00:39:32.650
to be very clear.

00:39:32.650 --> 00:39:37.410
But yeah, I'm clear that
even though the world is

00:39:37.410 --> 00:39:41.220
getting better by
almost every measure--

00:39:41.220 --> 00:39:44.030
the cost of food,
energy, water, health

00:39:44.030 --> 00:39:47.040
care, all these things are
plummeting as life is going up,

00:39:47.040 --> 00:39:49.200
as childhood
mortality rates have

00:39:49.200 --> 00:39:53.580
plummeted from 45% percent
of kids dying under age 5

00:39:53.580 --> 00:39:55.200
to now 4%.

00:39:55.200 --> 00:39:58.900
All of these metrics are
getting better and better.

00:39:58.900 --> 00:40:00.460
And I think they'll continue to.

00:40:00.460 --> 00:40:01.960
We're still going
to have terrorism.

00:40:01.960 --> 00:40:03.240
We're still going
to have warfare.

00:40:03.240 --> 00:40:05.323
We're still going to have
a whole bunch of things.

00:40:05.323 --> 00:40:08.320
The thing that gives
me the greatest hope

00:40:08.320 --> 00:40:12.390
for not being decimated is
that it's harder and harder

00:40:12.390 --> 00:40:14.690
to do anything in secret.

00:40:14.690 --> 00:40:17.360
It's the flip side
of loss of privacy,

00:40:17.360 --> 00:40:20.290
that there are cameras
all the time, everywhere.

00:40:20.290 --> 00:40:22.730
A single autonomous
car with a LIDAR

00:40:22.730 --> 00:40:25.690
generating 750 megabytes of data
as it's going down the roads.

00:40:25.690 --> 00:40:27.190
So everything is being imaged.

00:40:27.190 --> 00:40:28.720
Whatever augmented
reality goggles

00:40:28.720 --> 00:40:30.094
we're all going
to be wearing are

00:40:30.094 --> 00:40:34.030
going to have millimeter
cameras looking out.

00:40:34.030 --> 00:40:36.660
1.6 million drones flying over
the skies of the United States.

00:40:36.660 --> 00:40:38.380
So everything is going
to be visualized.

00:40:38.380 --> 00:40:40.270
And so your ability to
do something in secret

00:40:40.270 --> 00:40:42.250
becomes harder and harder.

00:40:42.250 --> 00:40:46.390
And that lets me sleep a
little bit better at night.

00:40:46.390 --> 00:40:49.120
But ultimately, when
I do my calculus,

00:40:49.120 --> 00:40:52.660
the question is are there
more good people in the world

00:40:52.660 --> 00:40:55.600
using these technologies or bad?

00:40:55.600 --> 00:40:56.709
AUDIENCE: Sure.

00:40:56.709 --> 00:40:58.375
PETER DIAMANDIS: I'll
leave that to you.

00:40:58.375 --> 00:40:58.780
AUDIENCE: All right.

00:40:58.780 --> 00:40:59.110
Thank you.

00:40:59.110 --> 00:40:59.710
PETER DIAMANDIS: Thank you.

00:40:59.710 --> 00:41:02.350
JACK HIDARY: So a final word of
advice to those in this room,

00:41:02.350 --> 00:41:04.630
on livestream, and going
to watch this on YouTube

00:41:04.630 --> 00:41:07.270
around the world,
you're at a company

00:41:07.270 --> 00:41:08.650
like Google or another company.

00:41:08.650 --> 00:41:12.395
You're managing 5, 10, 20
people, maybe 100 people.

00:41:12.395 --> 00:41:14.020
What is your advice
to somebody as they

00:41:14.020 --> 00:41:17.440
are growing their career, as
they're building products,

00:41:17.440 --> 00:41:21.040
to tap in to the kind
of exponential focus

00:41:21.040 --> 00:41:23.690
that you have and
you live every day?

00:41:23.690 --> 00:41:26.590
But in the practical
day-to-day sense,

00:41:26.590 --> 00:41:28.156
what is your advice to folks?

00:41:28.156 --> 00:41:29.530
PETER DIAMANDIS:
So first of all,

00:41:29.530 --> 00:41:33.400
don't do anything you don't
absolutely love doing.

00:41:33.400 --> 00:41:36.440
I don't know how to say
it more clearly than that.

00:41:36.440 --> 00:41:38.320
To do anything big
and bold in the world

00:41:38.320 --> 00:41:41.080
and make a difference
on the planet is hard.

00:41:41.080 --> 00:41:42.910
It's extraordinarily hard.

00:41:42.910 --> 00:41:45.610
And if you don't love
doing what you're doing,

00:41:45.610 --> 00:41:48.850
you're going to give up
before you get there.

00:41:48.850 --> 00:41:53.320
So any of my successes
are overnight successes

00:41:53.320 --> 00:41:54.850
after 11 years of hard work.

00:41:54.850 --> 00:41:56.280
And I just did not--

00:41:56.280 --> 00:41:57.490
I refused to give up.

00:41:57.490 --> 00:42:00.820
And sometimes there's an
important point to give up.

00:42:00.820 --> 00:42:01.630
But I didn't.

00:42:01.630 --> 00:42:05.530
Because for XPRIZE, like my
Zero G company, which-- anybody

00:42:05.530 --> 00:42:07.880
here flown in zero g?

00:42:07.880 --> 00:42:09.360
Mark has, I know.

00:42:09.360 --> 00:42:11.950
It took 11 years to
get FAA permission

00:42:11.950 --> 00:42:13.550
to do this with a 727.

00:42:13.550 --> 00:42:15.550
I had a chance to fly
Stephen Hawking in zero g.

00:42:15.550 --> 00:42:17.610
It was amazing.

00:42:17.610 --> 00:42:18.860
But I just refused to give up.

00:42:18.860 --> 00:42:21.084
I mean, I was battling the FAA.

00:42:21.084 --> 00:42:23.500
And I always think, you're
going to die or retire before I

00:42:23.500 --> 00:42:25.390
give up, was my attitude.

00:42:25.390 --> 00:42:30.460
And sometimes-- only because
I cared about it that much.

00:42:30.460 --> 00:42:31.820
The other parts is--

00:42:31.820 --> 00:42:34.149
and this is one of
the ethos of Google--

00:42:34.149 --> 00:42:36.190
that the world's biggest
problems are the world's

00:42:36.190 --> 00:42:38.490
biggest business opportunities.

00:42:38.490 --> 00:42:41.620
I mean, I tell people
probably the company that's

00:42:41.620 --> 00:42:44.230
made the biggest positive
impact on the planet

00:42:44.230 --> 00:42:47.950
is Google, in terms of-- and
you don't have to be a nonprofit

00:42:47.950 --> 00:42:51.310
to create an empirically
better world.

00:42:51.310 --> 00:42:53.410
And then, when I
become a billionaire,

00:42:53.410 --> 00:42:54.940
help a billion people.

00:42:54.940 --> 00:42:57.130
So it's those kinds
of mindsets, I think,

00:42:57.130 --> 00:43:02.030
that are convergent with
the power that you have.

00:43:02.030 --> 00:43:05.680
Never underestimate
what you can do.

00:43:05.680 --> 00:43:08.620
Each of you are extraordinarily
powerful to solve problems.

00:43:08.620 --> 00:43:10.960
You just have to have
that committed, passionate

00:43:10.960 --> 00:43:11.460
human mind.

00:43:11.460 --> 00:43:12.251
JACK HIDARY: Great.

00:43:12.251 --> 00:43:12.790
Peter--

00:43:12.790 --> 00:43:13.050
PETER DIAMANDIS: Thank you.

00:43:13.050 --> 00:43:14.632
JACK HIDARY: Thank
you very much.

00:43:14.632 --> 00:43:15.590
Great to have you here.

00:43:15.590 --> 00:43:18.940
[APPLAUSE]

